In this line:

    const data = this.getLessonById(activity.id)
                     .flatMap(subLesson =&gt; recursivelyGetActivityObservales(subLesson));

the function `recursivelyGetActivityObservales(subLesson)` is returning an **array**, not an Observable. FlatMap/mergeMap operators need to **return an observable** in order to work properly.

I don&#39;t know what you will do with your final array of observables, but if you are gone a merge it anyway, a quick solution is use the `merge()` operator. Example:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const lessons = (activity) =&gt; [
        rxjs.from([1, 2, 3, 4]),
        rxjs.from([1, 2, 3, 4]),
        rxjs.from([1, 2, 3, 4]),
        rxjs.from([1, 2, 3, 4])
    ]

    const activity = rxjs.of(&#39;activity1&#39;);

    const toSub = activity.pipe(rxjs.operators.mergeMap((activity) =&gt; rxjs.merge(...lessons(activity))))

    toSub.subscribe(console.log)

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/rxjs/6.5.3/rxjs.umd.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

In your code:

    const data: Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt; = this.getLessonById(activity.id)
                 .flatMap(subLesson =&gt;  merge(...recursivelyGetActivityObservales(subLesson)));
    obsList.push(data);


**Preferred Solution:**

Said that, IMO the correct **solution** would be just returning the type `Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt;`, since it also represents multiple DataEntity objects. There is no reason to have an array of observables in this use case.

 For that, I would just return the merged list. 
Example:

    const recursivelyGetActivityObservales = (currentLesson: DataEntity): Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt; =&gt; {
        const obsList: Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt;[] = [];

        const activities: any[] = currentLesson.get(&#39;reference&#39;);
        for (const activity of activities) {
            if (activity[&#39;type&#39;] === &#39;lesson&#39;) {
                const data = this.getLessonById(activity.id).flatMap(subLesson =&gt;  recursivelyGetActivityObservales(subLesson));
                obsList.push(data);
            } else {
                const loadedActivity = this.activitiesService.getActivityEntity(+activity.id);

                if (loadedActivity) {
                    obsList.push(from([loadedActivity]));
                } else {
                    obsList.push(this.activitiesService.loadActivitiesFromId(activity.id));
                }
            }
        }

        return merge(...obsList);
    }

**Explantaion:**

An `Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt;` is a data structure that emits DataEntities (0, 1 or **many**) over and scheduler. So is actually a container (like an array) of DataEntities.
Take this example, where both data structure equals the same output result:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const lessonObsArray =  [ // Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt;[]
        rxjs.of(1),
        rxjs.of(2),
        rxjs.of(3),
        rxjs.of(4),
    ]

    const lessonObs = rxjs.merge( // Observable&lt;DataEntity&gt;
        rxjs.of(1),
        rxjs.of(2),
        rxjs.of(3),
        rxjs.of(4)
    );

    lessonObsArray.forEach(obs =&gt; obs.subscribe(console.log))
    console.log(&#39;--------&#39;)
    lessonObs.subscribe(console.log)
    // They emit the same!!! (a collection of numbers in this case)

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/rxjs/6.5.3/rxjs.umd.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


Hope this helps!

